The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | T20 League from October 8
                                                   T20 League from October 8
            A STAFF REPORTER                      
	Calcutta: The inaugural edition of the Champions League Twenty20 will be held from October 8 to 23 in India, it was announced at a press conference by the three founding members  the Board of Control for Cricket in India, Cricket Australia and Cricket South Africa  at Johannesburg on Sunday.         
	The twelve-team extravaganza will comprise of three teams from India (two finalists and the top league finishing team), who will compete against the top two domestic T20 teams from South Africa, England, Australia and the domestic T20 champions from New Zealand, West Indies and Sri Lanka.         
	The teams will be divided into four groups of three each. The top two teams from each group will qualify for the second stage from where four teams would make it to the semi-finals.         
	The Royal Challengers Bangalore, the Deccan Chargers and the Delhi DareDevils will represent India. Victoria and New South Wales will represent Australia, while the Cobras and the Eagles will represent South Africa.         
	The Deccan Chargers captain Adam Gilchrist said: Champions League Twenty20 will provide a different level of stimulus as we will test our strength and our strategies against the best in the world.         
	Anil Kumble, captain of the Royal Challengers Bangalore, said on the occasion: We have achieved our first aim of qualifying for the Champions League Twenty20. We are keen to ensure that the second aim of winning Indian Premier League and being the lead representative from India is achieved later this evening.         
	We have learnt a lot by competing in the two editions of the IPL and are hopeful that we will do India proud by holding the Champions League Twenty20 trophy later this year.                                                                                                                       
